{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὄχθη</b>, ἡ, <br /> older form of ὄχθος, <b>any height</b> or <b>rising ground</b>, natural or artificial, <b>bank, dyke</b> by the side of a river, ὑψηλὴν βάλεν ὄχθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.171, compare 172: in _sing._, also, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Publicola” 16, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Anabasis” 1.14.4, “CPHerm.” 95.10 (3rd c.AD)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: mostly in <i>plural</i>, <b>raised banks of a river</b>, in full, ποταμοῖο παρ᾽ ὄχθας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.487, 18.533, compare 3.187; παρ᾽ ὄχθῃσιν ποταμοῖο 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.97; Καφισοῦ παρ᾽ ὄχθαις 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.46, compare 6th c.BC: Xenophanes Poeta Philosophus 2.21, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 810, “Th.” 392, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὄχθαι καπέτοιο the <b>raised banks</b> of the trench, <b>dykes</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.356 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; also, <b>heights</b> beside the sea, ἁλὸς παρ᾽ ὄχθας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.132 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ταὶ ὑπὲρ Κύμας ἁλιερκέες ὄ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.18, compare 12.2 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also of <b>rising banks</b> at a little distance from a river, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 4.3.3 and 5: ὄχθη\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] is distinguished as <b>the bank of a river</b>, from ὄχθος <b>a hill</b>, in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 726, 729 (both Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; and this distinction generally holds, but in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 1.64 we read ὄχθαις ὑπὸ Ταϋγέτου\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; and in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 1132 (Lyric poetry), Νυσαίων ὀρέων ὄχθα; reversely, we have in Sapph. p.44 Lobel, ὄχθοις Ἀχέροντος\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1161, Ἀχερουσίους ὄχθους\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; and in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 655, Ἰσμήνιον πρὸς ὄχθον\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; in late Prose, τὴν ὄχθαν (sic) τῆς θαλάσσης sea- <b>shore</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.AD: Aëtius Medicus 2.203.\">Refs 6th c.AD+</a>] —Cf. ὄχθος.","strongNumber":"G8573","accentedUnicode":"ὄχθη","shortDef":"a riverbank","mediumDef":"a riverbank","stepGloss":"a riverbank","stepTransliteration":"ochthē","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}